Relentless exhaustion is a common side effect of both depression and severe heartbreak. Just getting out of bed in the morning can be an overwhelming and excruciating experience.
Depression is not a state of mind you consciously or logically choose.

Depression isn‚Äôt rational or emotional - it isn‚Äôt a straightforward response to a tough situation. Depression just is, like December‚Äôs weather in Seattle. It lingers, and it‚Äôs hard to wrap your mind around if you haven‚Äôt experienced it.
While depression disconnects us from our human emotions, and therefore must be carefully addressed, heartbreak by itself can actually help us move through our emotions.
Depression is not simply a deeper state of heartbreak or sadness, and it‚Äôs often misunderstood.

It‚Äôs super easy for people to say ‚Äúpositive‚Äù things like that with the best of intentions, but when you‚Äôre suffering from depression or severe heartbreak these kinds of clich√©d phrases often come across the wrong way - thoughtless, empty, and essentially worthless.
There are times when depression can leave you feeling dead inside, incapable of moving and doing the things you used to enjoy.
Heartbreak can be a trigger for depression, but depression is something altogether different.
Depression, on the other hand, is often flat, hollow, and insufferable - literally sapping a person of emotion, hope and reason.
Even though depression makes you feel hopelessly alone, that‚Äôs often exactly what depression motivates you to seek - more isolation.

Depression is one of the most helpless and tiring emotional experiences a person can live through. Sometimes it‚Äôs feeling totally disoriented, sometimes it‚Äôs feeling completely hopeless, and sometimes it‚Äôs feeling absolutely nothing at all.
People suffering from depression typically get anxious with feeling like they‚Äôre a burden on their loved ones. This causes them to isolate themselves and push away the very people they need.

Remind yourself that depression, and to a lesser degree, heartbreak, can take almost everything away. All your actions and words should come from a place of love, but that doesn‚Äôt mean your depressed or heartbroken loved one will always be loving in return, and that‚Äôs OK.
Depression and heartbreak can both exhaust the human spirit.

anyway, because of the way our society is structured, a lot of the heightened stigma on bipolar is the assumption that people will be less productive than people with unipolar depression because they think the condition lasts longer and is more disabling

additionally, I think bipolar is viewed as more "serious" or "severe" than major depression
complete with the usual idea that the manic stages of bipolar are also more "serious" or "severe" than the depressive ones

I feel like one of the disparities between how bipolar and major depression are treated is that bipolar is usually understood to be a chronic condition while depression is often societally viewed as a temporary problem people can "just get over" through personal effort or therapy

I officially have bipolar, and while I think it's important to talk more about the specific stigma our conditions face, including from other mentally ill people, I hate this framing
